  "doc_id": "38360",
  "text": "each year, and nearly 850,000 new cases occur [1, [CITATION_1] . Hepatocellular carcinoma (HCC) accounts for 85-90% of all liver cancers and has received public attention. Despite rapid advances in new tests and treatments, the 5-year survival rate for HCC is still less than one in five [CITATION_2] . At present, surgery is still the main treatment for early liver cancer [CITATION_3] . However, a significant proportion of patients will have postoperative recurrence or distant metastasis [CITATION_4] . Recently, drugs such as sorafenib and regorafenib have been shown to be effective against advanced HCC [CITATION_5] [CITATION_6] . It is worth mentioning that patients with the same pathological type and clinical stage often have different outcomes after the same treatment, which is mainly due to the genetic heterogeneity of patients [CITATION_7] .",
